{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff: three source clients plus aggregation payload to the summary step. A single-function unit test can miss wiring/field-mapping omissions between modules (MOCK-MISS). REAL-INFRA is not required because source responses can be provided by in-process fakes. Rejected System because behavior text is about what is passed to summary generation, not real network/OS behavior; rejected Agentic because it does not check model judgment, only pre-LLM payload completeness.","test_description":"Wire real collector/assembler modules with fake source adapters returning distinct sentinel values per source. Execute collection + payload build, intercept the exact input sent to summary-generation, and assert all three source sections/keys are present and correctly mapped.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is cross-module error propagation and fallback rendering (collector -> report composer), so Unit is too low for the real failure boundary. Can be reproduced with one source adapter raising timeout/503 in-process; no mandatory real OS/network needed (REAL-INFRA no). Rejected System because behavior text only requires graceful degradation semantics, which a deterministic failing adapter reproduces. Rejected Agentic because correctness is presence of fallback note and non-abort, not LLM output quality.","test_description":"Run report generation with two successful fake sources and one fake source that raises an availability error. Assert pipeline completes, output contains `data unavailable` in that section, and other sections still include their data.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary accurately represents the key values present in the input data.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on model-generated content fidelity (LLM-DEP yes). A stubbed summarizer would always pass format checks while hiding hallucination/omission/misstatement failures (MOCK-HIDE). Rejected Workflow because behavior text specifies a single summary-generation judgment, not multiple agentic decisions in sequence.","test_description":"Feed representative weekly datasets with known key values to the real summary model and evaluate whether produced narrative preserves those values/relationships (with rubric or semantic checks) across repeated runs to account for output variance.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real failure boundary includes external email transport/inbox delivery and end-to-end infrastructure (REAL-INFRA yes). In-process mocks can hide SMTP/API auth, envelope formatting, provider acceptance, and inbox routing failures (MOCK-HIDE). Rejected Agentic because behavior text is delivery success to inbox, not semantic quality of model output; the summary content can be fixture-controlled for this test. Rejected Workflow because there is no requirement for multiple agentic decisions.","test_description":"Execute scheduled run in an environment using real service endpoints (or staging equivalents), then verify a message is actually received in the configured mailbox with expected subject/body/report attachment content markers.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.7,"Agentic":0.15,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable, the generated report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary risk is orchestration/state handoff across modules and runs: delivery failure handling, filesystem persistence, and retry logic. This is above Unit because it spans generator, mailer, persistence, and scheduler trigger modules (MOCK-MISS). Local filesystem and a failing mail adapter are sufficient; real network outage is not required to reproduce logic failure. Rejected System because behavior text focuses on fallback+retry semantics, which deterministic unreachable-mail errors can trigger without real transport.","test_description":"Run cycle 1 with mail client stubbed to unreachable; assert report persisted to disk and marked pending. Run cycle 2 with mail client recovering; assert pending report is retried/sent and local pending artifact/state is cleared or updated per policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.57,"System":0.3,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.05}}]}
